TY  - JOUR
T1  -  Erratum: Note on Proposition 1( a-b ) in Dal Bó, Finan and Rossi (2013)—Strengthening State Capabilities: The Role of Financial Incentives in the Call to Public Service, The Quarterly Journal of Economics 128 (3): 1169–1218 *
PY  - 2015
Y1  - 2015/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjv009
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 130
IS  - 2
SP  - 1003
EP  - 1009
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  -  Our paper includes a theoretical section featuring a model of an employer that posts a wage to fill a vacancy in the public sector. Workers then choose whether to apply for the position or not. Workers differ along two dimensions, namely quality and public sector motivation (PSM). A first proposition relegated to the Online Appendix characterizes the applicant pool for a given wage. A subsequent proposition (Proposition 1 in the paper) establishes comparative statics of wage changes on the average level of the two traits among applicants. This proposition asserts that when traits are independently distributed in the population, an increase in wages will increase the size and average quality of the applicant pool (Proposition 1( a )) and decrease its average PSM (Proposition 1( b )). This result resonates with previous contributions cited in our paper, and captures a standard concern that raising wages may attract talented people to public service at the cost of also attracting people who are less motivated. In stating Proposition 1( a-b ), we intended but failed to include a restriction to uniformly distributed traits. The concise proof in our online appendix, to be valid, depended on an unstated restriction. The restriction to uniformly distributed traits is not required to establish that higher wages increase the size of the applicant pool. But some restriction beyond independence is necessary to rule out situations where higher wages can have positive effects on both traits. Correlation between the applicant traits can also create those situations, as studied in Proposition 1( c ), where an increase in wages improves quality in the applicant pool but also, against the standard concern, improves PSM. In what follows we place the restriction to uniform distributions and show that Proposition 1( a-b ) indeed follows, laying out a detailed proof. To make this note self-contained, we first characterize the applicant pool (repeating the first proposition of the Online Appendix), although the indifference condition characterized therein does not hinge on distributional assumptions. 
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjv009
ER  - 



